<subSubSection pageNumber="887" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="887">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="887">Note:</emphasis>
Powrie (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="887">J. S. African Bot.</emphasis>
38: 303. 1972) incorrectly treated this name as homotypic with 
<taxonomicName authority="L. (1753)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bruniaceae" genus="Brunia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Bruniales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nodiflora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="887">Brunia nodiflora</emphasis>
L. (1753)
</taxonomicName>
, typified by material in the Clifford herbarium. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Thuja" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cupressoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="887">Thuja cupressoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an independent name and Farjon (
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="887">Monogr</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Sciadopitys" authorityName="Sciadopitys" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="887">Cupressaceae</emphasis>
Sciadopitys
</taxonomicName>
: 471. 2005) indicated the cited Shaw plate as the 
<typeStatus>
<typeStatus>holotype</typeStatus>
</typeStatus>
(which it is not). It may well be the obvious choice as 
<typeStatus>
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
</typeStatus>
, but because 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Farjonâ€™s">Farjon's</normalizedToken>
statement was published after 1 Jan 2001, the omission of the phrase &quot;designated here&quot; or an equivalent (Art. 7.11) means that the choice is not effective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
